<HEAD>With AM-Caterpillar-Deere-UAW Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a look at the operations of
Caterpillar Inc., the world's largest maker of earth-moving
equipment and machinery:
   Headquarters: Peoria, Ill.
   Employees: 58,797 worldwide.
   Hourly United Auto Workers employees: 17,553 active, 1,000 on
layoff.
   Earnings: $263 million on sales of $4.5 billion in first six
months of fiscal 1988.
   Current average hourly wages for union workers: $14.61 an hour,
or $30,388 a year.
   Contract: Current 27-month agreement ratified July 8, 1986, with
expiration at midnight Friday. Contract negotiations started Aug. 4.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>AFFECTED PLANTS AND THEIR UNION WORKERS</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Illinois: 2,445 workers at Aurora, 1,978 at Decatur, 648 at
Pontiac, and 10,033 at all Peoria-area facilities including East
Peoria, Mapleton, Mossville and Morton.
   Iowa: 222 at Davenport; plant to be closed by the end of 1988.
   Colorado: 145 at Denver.
   Tennessee: 34 at Memphis.
   Pennsylvania: 2,048 at York.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>DOMESTIC OPERATIONS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Manufacturing plants</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
